{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487337"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:06:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:06:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"323"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/323"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.73,0.03,0.11,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92372"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/323"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"323"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75677"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"331"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31522"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31523"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44455"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92372"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents with a one month history of epigastric discomfort, associated with dizziness and feeling faint. The symptoms seem to be worse after a meal. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes, a knee arthroplasty and gastric bypass surgery three months ago. He has recently been started on verapamil for angina.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhysical examination is unremarkable apart from a BMI of 29.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Drug side-effect","Dumping syndrome","Insulinoma","Gastroparesis","Para-oesophageal hernia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHis symptoms fit well for \u003Cstrong\u003Edumping syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. This term is used to describe the early and uncoordinated emptying of food from the stomach into the small bowel. There are two components to dumping. An early phase, occurring some 15 minutes after a meal when the patient experiences vasomotor symptoms of dizziness, light-headedness and nausea. These symptoms reflect a relative hypovolaemia, brought on by fluid shifts secondary to the sudden delivery of highly osmotic materials into the small bowel. The late phase of dumping may occur an hour or later after a meal and the symptoms are predominantly a reflection of a reactive hypoglycaemia that may occur after a sudden release of insulin (and over-compensation) to handle a large amount of high carbohydrate suddenly appearing in the small bowel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDumping used to be a well recognised sequela of the various procedures (gastric resection, vagotomy) that were performed in the treatment of chronic duodenal ulcer disease. Whilst the aim of these procedures was to reduce acid secretion, all too often they were accompanied by side-effects worse than the symptoms of the original disease. In the era of bariatric surgery, the symptoms of dumping are being seen more frequently as a side-effect of gastric bypass, where food can rapidly pass in an undigested state into the small bowel. Some 85% of patients undergoing a Roux-en-Y gastric bypass will experience some form of dumping - reinforcing the need for them to adhere to an appropriate diet.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGastroparesis and dumping both result from disturbance of the mechanics of gastric emptying.  However, the symptoms experienced by the two conditions are very different. With gastroparesis there is early satiety, postprandial fullness and nausea and/or vomiting. There is delayed gastric emptying. With dumping, the emptying is more rapid and uncontrolled.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The dumping syndrome is a relatively common consequence of gastric bypass surgery and can usually be managed by dietary advice."],"references":["Berg P, McCallum R. Dumping Syndrome: A Review of the Current Concepts of Pathophysiology, Diagnosis, and Treatment. Dig Dis Sci 2016; 61:11-18.","Vavricka SR, Greuter T. Gastroparesis and Dumping Syndrome: Current Concepts and Management. J Clin Med 2019; 8:1127-41."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75677"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"323"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75677"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T14:13:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T14:13:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"323"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92372"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},